## Note regarding update:connections_options

The update:connections_options scope grants the ability to modify the options field of Auth0 connections (client IDs, secrets, scopes, domains etc.). In isolation that sounds sensitive, but in this context it is not a security risk for the following reasons:

1. The "Terraform" client already had broad management permissions

The Terraform application was already granted scopes to create, read, update and delete connections, clients, actions and other Auth0 resources. The ability to update connection options is a subset of what it could already do — adding this scope doesn't materially expand its attack surface.

2. It's a machine-to-machine credential stored securely

The client_id and client_secret for the "Terraform" application are stored in AWS Secrets Manager (auth0_saml), access-controlled by IAM policies. Only the GitHub Actions CI pipeline can retrieve them.

3. It's scoped to Auth0 configuration only

update:connections_options can only modify Auth0 connection configuration — it cannot affect AWS resources, user data, or the SAML authentication flow directly.

4. All changes are auditable and version controlled

Any connection changes made by Terraform are driven by code in aws-root-account, reviewed via pull requests, and logged in both GitHub Actions and Auth0 audit logs.

5. Principle of least privilege is maintained relative to purpose

Terraform's purpose is to fully manage the Auth0 tenant configuration. Granting it the scopes it needs to do that job completely is correct. Withholding update:connections_options was an omission, not an intentional restriction — evidenced by the deprecation notices.

See also https://auth0.com/docs/troubleshoot/product-lifecycle/deprecations-and-migrations#new-management-api-scopes-required-for-connection-options